WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.120
gt right now is my favorite package for building pretty data display tables. It offers a bunch

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:09.120
of tools to help you get your display tables exactly the way you want them to look. One thing

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:14.080
I love is the calls merge helper function. It lets you combine multiple values into a single table

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:19.440
column. For example, suppose we have a data set with separate variables for latitude and longitude

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:24.320
but we want to combine them into a coordinates column in our display table. Calls merge lets us

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:29.040
select the columns to merge and define how they should look when combined. Now look at the station

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.400
name and caption variables. Suppose we want to combine these two into a single column and clean

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:41.520
up those missing values. Here we add the station caption only if the caption exists. I don't know

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.400
about you but before gt I found myself using dplyr's mutate function to handle these kind of

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:51.680
column merging actions. But that's not right. You often have to convert numeric factor or date time

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:57.840
values into text and doing so you lose information like order and things can get weird fast. These

00:00:57.840 --> 00:00:59.919
gt helper functions help you avoid these.

